"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. I was listening to a couple of friends of mine have a discussion the other day about gold versus Bitcoin. And the idea was that they didn't trust uh the way things were going, they didn't trust the dollar, they didn't trust the pre trajectory of our economy and our culture and everything else, just like a lot of us are kind of uh fearful about the future. And so they were discussing what's the best avenue to get security into the future, gold or bitcoin. What was going to be the currency that they could use in the future to buy stuff that they wouldn't be able to use dollars for that however it works. And I thought to myself, is that really the the currency that we're gonna be using? What if those little tokens aren't that effective at buying things in the future? What if they're not that valuable? I mean, you can look at gold and say that's been really valuable for a real long time, but not in every situation when there is gold. But a lot of times there's no gold out there, and people need much more fundamental things. Uh I I'm reminded of uh stories about post-World War II Europe where chocolate, cigarettes, coffee, sugar, these were the things that really had your currency. Everything else is just a means of getting those things. And so I thought to myself, you know, what is what is currency? It's what's current, it's what spends right now. And at the end of the day, the true currency is food, the true currency is water. That's the stuff that you need all the time that goes back. That you have to get, and it has to be current. So my future plans are going to be to provide food. I'm not gonna worry about which currency is going to get me my my you know, gas or my furniture, you know, all the things that you'll need to buy. Yeah, yeah. Maybe those things will be around, maybe they won't, who knows. In my prepper mind, the thing I want to, my bank is my soil and my currency is my food. So that's my goal and that's what I'm doing. Tha